On Sun, 4 Feb 2001 mrettig@... wrote:
&gt;&gt; Has anyone else found the construction of test suites to be largely a 
&gt;&gt; waste of time? IMO, if you use packages properly, then you should 
&gt;&gt; never need to construct a test suite. 
&gt;Joi Ellis wrote:
&gt;No, not really.  I like having suite() because it allows me to trim out
&gt;tests I don&#39;t need to run without having to delete the sources for them.
&gt;I have a number of tests which, unfortunately, require manual 
intervention
&gt;to click buttons on swing dialogs, and I leave these commented out in
&gt;the suite() method most of the time so that nightly automated tests run
&gt;unattended.

For selectivity on tests, I would use a subclass of TestCase that 
identifies the test as requiring user intervention. This way you could 
have different types of runs, such as your nightly run or a simple debug 
run that requires a user to click the buttons. Or if you use Ant, you can 
use a patternset to exclude certain tests on the nightly build.

The process of removing/adding tests to the suite is the very process that 
I try to avoid. What happens if you forget to readd an excluded test 
method to the suite? You&#39;re tests will probably run and give you a false 
positive.  Since I never use suites, I&#39;ve never, ever had a false positive 
due to a coder failing to properly update a suite. 

&gt;Suite() methods also allow me to control the runtime order without
&gt;playing games like manually rearranging source code or changing method
&gt;names so that a reflection-based runtime can be coerced into running the
&gt;tests in the order I want them run.

The ordering of methods is one area where suites may be convenience, but 
this is a rare case.  If the runtime order is worth the extra maintenance 
and risk, then go for it.

Regards,
Mike
